  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act strengthened anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n2. Major Legislative Developments:\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- International cooperation and information sharing\n- Expanded definition of financial institutions\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n\n3. Global Regulatory Frameworks:\n- FATF recommendations\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n4. Technology Integration:\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Artificial intelligence for detecting suspicious patterns\n- Enhanced digital verification processes\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Increased focus on emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to new financial technologies and evolving criminal strategies.",
